**Strategy 3: Use newer base image**\nIf possible, use a newer base image that has autoconf 2.71+ in its repositories.\n\n**Strategy 4: Skip libtiff autoreconf**\nIf libtiff doesn\'t absolutely need to be built from source, use pre-built libtiff or modify the build process to skip autoreconf.\n\n**Strategy 5: Patch libtiff\'s configure.ac**\nModify libtiff\'s configure.ac to accept older autoconf version (least recommended, may cause compatibility issues).\n\n**Pattern Recognition:**\n- This is a classic "outdated base image" problem in OSS-Fuzz\n- When default repositories don\'t have required versions, building from source is often the most reliable solution\n- The autoconf version requirement is strict and non-negotiable for libtiff\n\n**Critical Considerations:**\n1. **Build order matters**: Autoconf must be installed BEFORE libtiff build starts\n2. **Version verification**: After installation, verify autoconf version with `autoconf --version`\n3. **Dependency chain**: Ensure automake and other autotools are compatible with autoconf 2.71\n4. **Minimal impact**: The fix should not break other dependencies\n\n**Recommended Approach:**\nBuild autoconf 2.71 from source. This is the most reliable approach as it:\n1. Doesn\'t depend on repository availability\n2. Guarantees the correct version\n3. Is isolated from other system packages\n4. Can be cleanly integrated into the Dockerfile\n\n**Implementation Plan:**\n1. Add build dependencies (wget, build-essential)\n2. Download autoconf 2.71 source\n3. Build and install to /usr\n4. Verify installation\n5. Continue with existing build steps\n\n**Risk Assessment:**\n- **Low risk**: Building autoconf from source is standard practice\n- **Medium complexity**: Requires adding multiple commands to Dockerfile\n- **High reward**: Should resolve the version mismatch issue definitively\n\n--- 【LESSONS FROM PREVIOUS ATTEMPTS】 ---\n- [Attempt 1] The build failed at the libtiff configuration stage due to insufficient autoconf version (requires 2.71+). The base image likely has an older autoconf version. This is a dependency/environment issue that needs to be fixed in the Dockerfile by installing a newer version of autoconf or using a different approach to build libtiff.\n- [Attempt 2] The build environment lacks sufficient autoconf version (2.71+ required). The Dockerfile installs autoconf-archive but not the main autoconf package. Need to install autoconf and potentially upgrade it to meet libtiff\'s requirements. This is a fundamental environment configuration issue that must be resolved before any compilation can proceed.\n- [Attempt 3] The fix to add autoconf package was applied but didn\'t resolve the issue. The installed autoconf version from default repositories is still < 2.71. This indicates the base image has outdated repositories. Need a more aggressive approach: either install autoconf 2.71+ from PPA/backports, build from source, or find alternative way to build libtiff without requiring newer autoconf.\n\n\n--- Configuration Files (Dockerfile, build.sh, etc.) ---\n\n### Content from: Dockerfile ###\n# Copyright 2019 Google Inc.\n#\n# Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");\n# you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.\n# You may obtain a copy of the License at\n#\n#      http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0\n#\n# Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software\n# distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,\n# WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.\n# See the License for the specific language governing permissions and\n# limitations under the License.\n#\n################################################################################\n\nFROM gcr.io/oss-fuzz-base/base-builder@sha256:a6e85b2d7c098ed87d8c51980d24ae07b262a2becf42fd099d02c90f07e51d98\nRUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y \\\n  autoconf \\\n  autoconf-archive \\\n  automake \\\n  autopoint \